{{Infobox software | name = Adobe Marketing Cloud | logo = | logo_size = 200 | logo caption = Adobe Marketing Cloud icon | screenshot = | caption = Adobe Marketing Cloud icon | developer = [[Adobe Systems]]<ref name="Adobe-AMC"/> | released = {{release date|mf=yes|2012|10|24}} | operating system = [[Windows]], [[Linux]], [[OS X]]<ref name="Adobe-AMC"/> | language = Multilingual | genre = [[Software suite]], [[cloud computing|cloud applications]] | license = [[Software as a service]] |website = {{URL|http://www.adobe.com/solutions/digital-marketing.html| Marketing Cloud page}} }}
'''Adobe Experience Cloud''' ('''AEC'''), formerly '''Adobe Marketing Cloud''' ('''AMC'''), is a collection of integrated online marketing and [[List of web analytics software|Web analytics products]] by [[Adobe Systems]].
==History== Adobe Marketing Cloud includes a set of [[analytics]], [[social]], [[advertising]], [[Social media optimization|media optimization]], [[Targeting (advertising)|targeting]], Web [[experience management]] and [[content management]] products<ref name="AMC">{{cite web |url=http://www.adobe.com/solutions/digital-marketing.html|title=Adobe Marketing Cloud solutions | publisher=Adobe Systems|accessdate=January 13, 2014}}</ref> aimed at the advertising industry and hosted on [[Amazon Web Services]].<ref name="Adobe-AMC">{{cite web |url=https://aws.amazon.com/marketplace/pp/B008BWCWHS/ref=srh_res_product_title?ie=UTF8&sr=0-2&qid=1391774874324 | title=Adobe Experience Manager |publisher=Amazon Web Services | accessdate=February 7, 2014 |author =Amazon Web Services}}</ref> Like other Adobe [[Cloud service]]s (e.g., [[Adobe Creative Cloud]]), the Adobe Marketing Cloud allows users with valid [[subscriptions]] to download the entire collection and use it directly on their computers with open access to online updates.<ref name="CNBC-AMC-sub">{{cite web | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100564321 | title=Why Investors Like Adobe Diving Into Subscriptions | publisher=Canada National Broadcasting Corp. | date=March 18, 2013 | accessdate=February 15, 2014 | author=Jon Fortt}}</ref>
The Adobe Marketing Cloud collection was introduced to the public in October 2012<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.adobe.com/press-release/adobe-marketing-cloud/media-alert-solutions-unveiled-adobe-marketing-cloud|title=Media Alert: Solutions Unveiled for Adobe Marketing Cloud; Provocative New Campaign Launches {{!}} Adobe Newsroom|website=news.adobe.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> as Adobe began retiring the [[Omniture]] name it acquired in October 2009.<ref name="Forbes-Omniture">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/09/16/adobe-omniture-advertising-cmo-network-adobe.html | title=Adobe Buys Omniture, Opens Gate to Advertising | publisher=Forbes magazine | date=September 16, 2009 | accessdate=January 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Associated Press">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/technology/companies/16adobe.html?_r=0 | title=Firm for Analyzing Web Traffic Bought by Adobe for $1.8 Billion|publisher=New York Times | date=September 15, 2009 | accessdate=January 5, 2014 | author=Associated Press}}</ref> Products of the defunct company were then integrated step by step into the new Cloud service<ref>{{cite news|url= http://searchengineland.com/how-to-gracefully-retire-a-brand-name-125611|title=How To Gracefully Retire A Brand Name|date=July 18, 2012|publisher=SearchEngineLand.com | author=Richard Carey}}</ref> which includes the following eight applications: Adobe Analytics, Adobe Target, Adobe Social, Adobe Experience Manager, Adobe Media Optimizer, Adobe Campaign, Audience Manager and Primetime. In November 2013, Adobe Systems introduced mobile features to its Marketing Cloud, making [[smartphones]] and other [[mobile devices]] new targets for analytics.<ref name="Forbes-AdobeMobile">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/roberthof/2013/11/07/adobe-takes-its-marketing-cloud-services-mobile/ | title=Adobe Takes Its Marketing Cloud Services Mobile | publisher=Forbes | date=November 7, 2013 | accessdate=January 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2061880/adobe-adds-geolocation-targeting-to-marketing-cloud.html| title=Adobe adds geolocation targeting to Marketing Cloud | publisher=PC World | date=November 7, 2013 |accessdate=January 14, 2014}}</ref><ref name="AMC-mobile">{{cite web|url=http://www.adobe.com/aboutadobe/pressroom/pressreleases/201311/110713AdobeLaunchesMobileServices.html | title=Adobe Launches Mobile Services for Adobe Marketing Cloud| publisher=Adobe Systems |accessdate=January 14, 2014}}</ref>
On September 15, 2009, [[Omniture]], Inc. and Adobe Systems announced that Adobe would be acquiring Omniture, an online marketing and web analytics business unit in [[Orem, Utah]].<ref name="Adobe-Omni-Acquisition">{{cite web |url=http://www.adobe.com/investor-relations/omniture-acquisition.html | title=Adobe acquires Omniture Software | publisher=Adobe Systems}}</ref> The deal of $1.8 billion, was completed on October 23, 2009,<ref name="Associated Press"/><ref name="NYT-AdobeOmniture">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/technology/companies/16adobe.html?_r=0 | title=Firm for Analyzing Web Traffic Bought by Adobe for $1.8 Billion|publisher=New York Times | date=September 15, 2009 | accessdate=January 18, 2014 | author=The Associated Press}}</ref> and is now joined by other Adobe acquisitions such as [[Day Software]] and [[Efficient Frontier (company)|Efficient Frontier]], as the main components of Adobe's Digital Marketing Business Unit.<ref name="Robin Wauters"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adobe.com/aboutadobe/invrelations/faq_omniture.html| title=Omniture acquisition FAQ|author =Adobe|date=2009-10-26}}</ref> Around 2012, Adobe withdrew the Omniture brand while its products were being integrated into the Adobe Marketing Cloud.<ref name="Robin Wauters">{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/11/30/adobe-acquires-efficient-frontier-to-boost-its-digital-marketing-solutions/| title=Adobe Acquires Efficient Frontier|author =Robin Wauters|date=2011-11-30|publisher=TechCrunch.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://searchengineland.com/how-to-gracefully-retire-a-brand-name-125611|title=How To Gracefully Retire A Brand Name|date=2012-07-18|publisher=SearchEngineLand.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.adobe.com/aboutadobe/invrelations/faq_omniture.html|title=Omniture acquisition FAQ|author =Adobe|date=2009-10-26}}</ref>
On May 21, 2018 Adobe announced the acquisition of [[Magento]] for 1.68$ billion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adobe to acquire Magento for 1.6B|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/21/adobe-to-acquire-magento-for-1-6-b/ |date=21 May 2018}}</ref> The addition of the Magento Commerce will enable commerce features to be integrated into the Adobe Experience Cloud.
In the same year, on September 20, 2018 Adobe acquired the marketing automation company [[Marketo]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Adobe buys Marketo for $4.75 billion |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/adobe-buys-marketo-for-4-75-billion|date=20 September 2018}}</ref>. The acquisition is expected to close in Q4 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adobe gets its company, snaring Marketo for $4.75 billion |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/09/20/adobe-gets-its-company-snaring-marketo-for-4-75-billion/ |date=20 September 2018}}</ref>
